The lost '''Wheelbarrow Mine''' is claimed to have been located about {{Convert|10|mi}} from [[Potlatch, Idaho|Potlatch]] in [[Latah County]], Idaho.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bookmark|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LU7pAAAAMAAJ|volume=17-18|year=1964|publisher=University of Idaho Library.|pages=153–|quote=Casper, one of the prospectors, and his un-named partner built a wheelbarrow of whiskey barrel staves, tunneled into the ... 5 1/2 miles of road and stripped several veins with a bulldozer at the Wheelbarrow mine about 10 miles from Potlatch.}}</ref><ref name="Jameson1993">{{cite book|author=W. C. Jameson|title=Buried Treasures of the Rocky Mountain West: Legends of Lost Mines, Train Robbery Gold, Caves of Forgotten Riches, and Indians' Buried Silver|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=58aSz0RZeZEC&pg=PA68|year=1993|publisher=august house|isbn=978-0-87483-272-3|pages=68–|quote=During the summer of 1880, a prospector known only as Caspar, along with his partner, roamed the wilds of the Moscow Mountains in ... As winter approached, Caspar's partner suggested they abandon the high ...}}</ref><ref name="Storm1947">{{cite book|author=Barry Storm|title=Practical prospecting: a manual of electronic prospecting technique|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LrM_AAAAIAAJ|year=1947|publisher=Southwest Pub. Co.|pages=36–|quote=Who "discovered" the Lost Wheelbarrow Mine in Idaho, the}}</ref>  The reported location is 3,871 feet above sea level, at coordinates 46.9975° N, 116.7833° W.<ref name=kne>{{cite news|title=Mine Lost for Years Believed Found in Idaho|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=266&dat=19400126&id=6VYwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nzsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3363,5941448&hl=en|accessdate=9 November 2015|work=[[Kentucky New Era]]|date=January 26, 1940}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idahogeology.org/Services/MinesAndMinerals/results.asp?switch=Reference&value=7273|title=Idaho Geological Survey - Home|work=idahogeology.org}}</ref> The mine, believed to have been dug prior to 1890, was said to have produced $20,000 in gold, before a falling-out between its operators led to its abandonment.<ref name=kne/> One of the operators later returned to the area to find the mine again, but was unsuccessful.<ref name=kne/> In June 1939, miners with the Fitsum Mining company uncovered an abandoned mine matching the description of the Wheelbarrow mine, containing human bone presumed to belong to the other operator.<ref name=kne/>

